{In this lecture, I want to present the most successful defensive strategies:
1."Activate your pieces." You should ignore material and prioritize the
activity. 2. "Activate the King." We all know the famous quote, "The king
should be safe in the middlegame and brave in the endgame" 3. "Building a
Fortress" 4. Sacrifice material to simplify in a theoretical draw 5.
Transposing to theoretically lost positions but with practical chances 6. When
you are defending, exchange as many pawns as you can In the following example,
GM Sokolov abandons the "a7" pawn and activates his rook.} 39... Rd8 $1 40.
Rxa7 Rd3 41. Ra3 (41. h5 $1 {This is the simplest defence. White should
realize that his position is not better and switch to the defensive mode. I
believe that Erik still wanted to play for a win.} Rxb3) 41... b5 42. b4 (42.
h5 $1 {It wasn't too late to switch to the defensive setup I showed you before.
}) 42... Rd4 43. Rb3 $2 {To evaluate the position, we need to compare the
position of both rooks} (43. h5 $1 $11 {This was the last chance}) 43... h5 $1
{From now on Black is on the driving seat} 44. Kg2 Kf7 45. Kf3 Rc4 46. Ke3 g5
$1 47. f4 $2 {Very strange decision. An important rule that you should
remember is that the defensive side is trying to exchange the maximum amount
of pawns.} (47. hxg5 $1 fxg5 48. f4 gxf4+ 49. gxf4 Ke6 50. Rd3 {White has
enough counterplay to save the game without troubles}) 47... gxh4 $1 48. gxh4
Kg6 $1 49. Rc3 $1 Rxb4 50. Rc5 $1 Rb3+ 51. Ke4 Rxb2 52. f5+ Kh6 53. Rc6 $1 Rb4+
$1 54. Kf3 $4 (54. Kd5 $1 {Again the active defense was better choice. This
was the only move which saves the game.} Rxh4 55. Rxf6+ Kg5 56. Rf8 $1 Rh1 (
56... b4 57. f6 Kg6 58. Ke5 $11) 57. f6 Kg6 58. f7 Kg7 59. Rb8 Kxf7 60. Rxb5
$11) 54... Rxh4 55. Rxf6+ Kg5 56. Rg6+ (56. Rb6 Rf4+ $19) (56. Rf8 Rf4+ 57. Ke3
Rxf5 $19) 56... Kxf5 57. Rb6 Rb4 0-1

