{Black has a pawn up, but it doesn't seem that simple to convert the advantage
to a full point. This is a classical situation in which Black should make a
decision. To activate his king and abandon the "f7" pawn or to play "safe" and
keep his extra pawn.} 1... Kh6 $1 (1... Kf8 $6 {Is the "safe" choice, but is
wrong here} 2. Kb3 Ke7 3. Ne4 {with the idea a3-a4. White has enough
counterplay to hold the draw.}) 2. Ne4 (2. Nxf7+ {is possible, but doesn't
solve the problems. The pawn is not important at all, and Black activates his
king.} Kh5) 2... Kh5 $1 {Of course, the "f6" and "h7" pawns are not that
important.} 3. Nxf6+ Kg5 4. Nxh7+ Kxf5 5. h4 Be3 $1 {Restricting the knight.
The threat is Bh6, followed by Kg6.} 6. Nf8 Kf4 7. Nd7 Bd4 8. Nf6 (8. h5 Kxf3
9. Kd3 (9. h6 e4 $19) 9... f5 10. h6 Bb2 $19 {followed by e5-e4}) 8... Kxf3 9.
Kd3 Kf4 10. Nd5+ Kg4 {Now is over. The "h" pawn is not going anywhere, and
Black's central pawns decide the game.} 11. Nc7 f5 12. Nxa6 f4 13. Nc7 f3 14.
Nxb5 Kh3 $1 {The last finess, now the "f" pawn is unstoppable and Botvinnik
resign.} 0-1

