{This classical example shows once again that the best chance to save hard
endgames is with active defense.} 1... Rd2 $1 {The best chance for Black. The
position remains objectively lost, but White needs to be very accurate.} (1...
Rd6 $6 {White wins here easily after:} 2. a4 Kg5 3. Ke2 $18) 2. Rxb6+ Kg5 3.
Ke1 (3. a4 $3 {This logical move still wins} Kg4 $5 4. Ke1 Rc2 5. a5 Kf3 6. a6
Re2+ (6... Rc1+ 7. Kd2 Ra1 8. Rf6 $1 f4 9. c4 $18) 7. Kd1 Kxf2 8. Rf6 (8. a7 $4
{leads only to draw after:} Re1+ 9. Kc2 Ra1 10. Rf6 Rxa7 11. Rxf5+ Ke2 {
Black has enough counterplay to save the game.}) 8... Rxb2 9. Rxf5+ Ke3 10. Ra5
Kd3 11. Kc1 Rb8 12. a7 Ra8 13. c4 Kxc4 14. Kd2 $18 {and White wins}) 3... Rc2
4. Rb5 $4 {this move is too slow} (4. a4 $1 {trying to transpose to the
variations below}) 4... Kg4 $1 5. h3+ (5. a4 $6 {It is too late for that.} f4
$19 {and Black is faster}) 5... Kxh3 6. Rxf5 Rxb2 7. Rf4 (7. a4 Ra2 8. a5 Kg4
9. Re5 Kf3) 7... Rxa2 {Now the draw is obvious} 8. Rxe4 h5 9. c4 Kg2 10. Rf4
Rc2 11. Rh4 Kf3 $1 {avoiding the last trap} (11... Rxf2 $2 12. Rh2+ $1 Kxh2 13.
Kxf2) 12. Kd1 Rxf2 13. c5 Ke3 14. Rxh5 Kd4 1/2-1/2

