34. Re1 {This is a quite recent example. Black is a pawn down but could save
the game. Svidler was in time trouble and made the wrong choice. Very often,
the simplest defensive strategy is to simplify to a well known theoretical
position. Black has a choice between 3 continuations: 34...Qxg2, 34...Rd4, 34..
.Rd1} Qxg2 $4 {Svidler played that in 2 seconds, and it appears that this is a
losing mistake.} (34... Rd4 $6 {looks tempting, but it is not entirely correct.
} 35. Qc3 $1 {Black still need to solve his problems.} Rb4+ 36. Kc1 Qf4+ 37.
Qe3 $16) (34... Rd1+ {was simple and strong} 35. Rxd1 Qxd1+ 36. Qc1 Qe2 $11 {
and White can't make any progress}) 35. Re7+ Ka8 36. Qf6 Qg1+ 37. Ka2 Qg8+ 38.
Rf7 1-0

