{[#]} 25. Re7+ {Nepomniachtchi shows great opening preparation and blitz out
25 moves. So far the young Esipenko finds the right defence. Here we reach the
critical point of the game.} Kg6 $4 {This is the case where the passive
defense was much better than the active one.} (25... Kg8 {and White has
nothing better than to force a draw after:} 26. Rxb7 a5 27. Re6 Ra6 28. Ree7
Rd8 $11) ({or even} 25... Kh8) 26. h5+ $1 Kg5 $8 (26... Kxh5 $4 27. Rg7 $18 {
[%cal Rd6d3,Rd3h3]}) (26... Kf5 27. Rd5+ Kf4 28. g3+ Kg4 29. Re4+ Kf3 30. Rdd4
Nc6 31. Re3#) 27. Rxb7 $2 (27. Rd3 $3 {The fantastic resource which Nepo
missed. Now Black king is getting mated in all lines.} f5 28. Re6 $3 {I will
not show you all the lines, but you can easily ask Stockfish. I am just
providing you with one variation, which illustrates White's idea.} Rc8 29. Rg3+
Kxh5 30. Re5 Rf8 31. Rg7 Nc6 32. Re3) 27... a5 28. g3 Ra6 29. Rxb8 Rxd6 30.
Rxf8 Rd2 31. a4 Ra2 32. Kg2 f5 33. Rc8 Rxa4 34. Rc5 {We reach the second
critical position of the game. Black saves the game very easily, but you need
to apply the defensive strategy that we already discussed: Simplifying the
position to a theoretical draw.} Ra2 {It is hard to say that this move is a
mistake, it is even the engines first line, but it is a step in the wrong
direction.} (34... Kxh5 $1 {this is the easiest draw} 35. Rxf5+ Kg6 36. Rb5 Rc4
37. Rxa5 Rxc3 {sooner or later, we will transpose to this endgame. If you
don't know how to hold it, you can have some problems, and probably that's why
Esipenko wants to avoid it.} 38. f4 {The the simplest way to make a draw is to
keep the rook on the third rank. Black is attacking the "g" pawn, and when
White plays g3-g4 or White's king is going to h4 then the rook is going on the
first rank and start giving checks from behind.} Rb3 39. Kh3 Rc3 40. Kh4 Rc1
41. f5+ (41. g4 Rh1+ $11) 41... Kf6 $11) 35. Kf3 {with a thread, g3-g4} Kf6 {
Esipenko panicked and made a mistake.} (35... a4 $1 36. g4 Kh4 $3 {And Black
is out of danger.} 37. Rxf5 Rc2 38. Rc5 a3 $11) 36. Ke3 $16 Kg5 37. f3 Kxh5 38.
Kf4 Kg6 39. Rc6+ Kg7 40. Kxf5 $18 {The rest is simple technique} Rf2 41. Rc7+
Kf8 42. f4 Rf3 43. g4 a4 44. c4 a3 45. Ra7 Rc3 46. Kf6 Ke8 47. c5 Rc4 48. f5
Rxg4 49. c6 Kd8 50. Rxa3 Kc7 51. Rh3 1-0

