{The second defensive strategy which I would like to show you is "Fortress."
Magnus Carlsen said that he didn't believe in Fortresses, but they actually
exist, and if you learn different types, you can save many games. The fortress
as an extreme and versatile defensive tool has naturally turned on the the
imagination of the study composers who have demonstrated numerous artistic
fortresses, partly with practical value and partly mere creatures of fantasy.
Here is one by the father of Modern study. Can white meet his opponent's
double threat? White cannot save his knight and stop the passed pawn and
should find a creative reply to the promotion.} 1. Nc6 $1 (1. Nd7 $2 d3 2. Nf6
{is refuted by the zwischenschach} Bb8+ $1 ({to avoid} 2... d2 3. g3+ Kg5 4.
Ne4+)) 1... d3 $1 2. Nxa7 $1 (2. Ne5 $2 {is met by} d2 3. f4 {with another
zwischenschach} Bg1+ $1 ({to avoid} 3... d1=Q $2 4. g3#)) 2... d2 3. Nb5 $1
d1=Q 4. Nc3 $1 Qd6+ 5. Kh1 $1 ({Not} 5. Kg1 $2 Qc5+) 5... Qe6 {Or any other
queen move.} (5... Kg5 6. Ne4+) (5... Kg3 6. Ne4+) 6. Ne4 $1 {The knight has
completed the sieg around the black king From now on dear reader it's your
move!} 1/2-1/2

