77. Bg5 {This is an amazing endgame. Here the defensive strategy is
straightforward: first, you need to realize that you are in danger. Then the
draw is achieved by sacrificing a pawn. Karjakin realized that if he reaches
the board's position but with the bishop on e6, he is winning.} (77. d5+ $2 {
now is premature} Kxd5 78. Kc7 Ke6 $11) (77. Ka7 {is not dangerous as well})
77... Be6 (77... f4 $1 {is a very simple draw.} 78. gxf4 Bf5 $11) 78. Bh6 $1 {
continuing with his plan} Bd7 $2 (78... f4 $1 $11 {the last chance}) 79. Bf4 $1
Be6 80. d5+ $3 $18 {amazing idea} Bxd5 (80... Kxd5 81. Kc7 {with the bishop on
"d7" king could go to "e6" and keep the kingside safe.} Kc4 82. Kd6 $18 {
and White is queening the e-pawn and then collecting the pawns on the
kingiside. Black's counterplay with the b-pawn is too slow}) 81. Kc8 $1 Bb3 82.
Kd8 Bc4 (82... Kd5 83. Ke7 Kc4 84. Kf7 Kxc3+ 85. Kxg6 $18) 83. Ke7 Bb3 84. e6
Bc4 85. Kf6 Bb3 86. Bc1 $1 {Karjakin is precise until the end} Bc4 87. Ba3 Bb3
88. e7 Kd7 89. Kxg6 1-0

