{[#] The last two examples are from my practice. I choose them because I want
to show you another defensive idea. When your position is lost, it makes sense
to try to transpose to a theoretically lost endgame, but where your opponent
can make a mistake.} 45. g4 {I remember that I had a powerful desire to resign,
but then I saw my chance. If I manage to eliminate all Black's pawns on the
kingside the position is draw.} h5 46. gxf5 gxf5 47. h4 Ke4 48. Ne6 Kf3 49. Ng7
Kg4 50. Ka1 Kxh4 (50... Ne2 {[%cal Re2f4] and I would resign, but my opponent
fell into the trap.}) 51. Nxf5+ Kg4 52. Ne3+ Kxf4 53. Ng2+ Kg3 54. Ne3 h4 $4 {
I should admit that here the smile comes back to my face.} (54... Kf3 55. Nf5
Nd5 $19) 55. Nf5+ Kg4 56. Nxh4 Kxh4 {This is a theoretical draw. It took a few
more moves for my opponent to realize that and to sign the scoresheet. Very
luck and undeserved draw for me.} 57. Kb2 Kg4 58. Ka1 Kf4 59. Kb2 Ke4 60. Ka1
Kd4 61. Kb2 Kc4 62. Ka1 Kb3 1/2-1/2

