{[%evp 0,80,39,5,26,32,34,40,16,16,25,28,28,26,32,35,26,25,38,40,63,70,58,70,
74,63,72,51,53,51,72,57,83,80,87,83,82,32,55,45,53,-15,16,36,13,-1,2,-51,-28,
-63,-50,-81,-77,-112,-4,-24,8,-65,2,-11,-10,-79,-106,-64,-100,-146,-138,-321,
-151,-152,-203,-184,-238,-290,-312,-357,-357,-612,-576,-622,-590,-611,-702]
The first two examples, taken from the practice of the Swedish grandmaster Ulf
Andersson, show how to prevent the opponent's attack before it starts. The
first critical position arises after White's 25.g4.} 1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3
e6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O Nc6 (6... Be7 7. d4 cxd4 8. Qxd4 d6) 7. e4 (7. d4
Nxd4 8. Nxd4 Bxg2 9. Kxg2 cxd4 10. Qxd4) 7... d6 8. d4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 10.
Qxd4 Be7 11. b3 O-O 12. Bb2 Qb8 {[%cal Gf8d8,Ge7f8] Intending to defend the
d6-pawn by ...Rd8 and then continue with ...Bf8 to protect the g7-pawn.} 13. h3
Rd8 14. Rad1 Bf8 15. Kh2 (15. f4 $2 d5 $1) 15... Nd7 16. f4 Bc6 17. b4 $6 {
This move weakens White`s queenside.} (17. Qf2 a6 18. f5 Ne5 19. fxe6 fxe6 20.
Ne2 {with the idea} Qc7 21. Nd4 Bd7 22. Nf3 Nxf3+ 23. Qxf3 $36) 17... a6 18. a4
{White prevents ...b6-b5, but this advance makes it possible for Black to
obtain later the c5-square for his knight after ...a6-a5.} Qc7 19. Rc1 {
Was better to keep the rook on d1 and defend on c4 by Rfe1 with Bf1 to follow.}
Bb7 20. Rfe1 Rac8 21. Bf1 Qb8 22. Qf2 a5 $1 23. b5 Nc5 24. Rcd1 Be7 25. g4 {
[%cal Bh3h4,Bg4g5,Bf2g3,Bh4h5,Bg5g6,Bf4f5,Bf5f6,Bh7h6,Bg8h7,Bd8h8] We have
reached the first critical position in the game - White's next few moves are
clear. If given enough time, Christiansen would proceed with Qg3 followed by
h3-h4-h5 and possibly g5-g6. In some positions, the advance f4-f5-f6 also
comes into consideration. Since Black cannot counterattack in the centre, he
should prevent White's attack before it happens. Andersson, comes with a
typical defensive setup that he likes a lot.} h6 {Looks dangerous for Black,
but Andersson prepares the following defensive manoeuvre.} 26. h4 Kh7 $1 {
[%cal Gg4g5,Gd8h8] Vacates the h8-square for the rook.} 27. Bh3 (27. g5 hxg5
28. hxg5 Rh8 29. Re3 Kg8+ 30. Rh3 Rxh3+ 31. Bxh3 Qc7 {[%csl Bc4,Be4,Ba4][%cal
Bg7g6,Be7f8,Bf8g7]} 32. Qe3 {with balanced situation.}) 27... Rc7 28. Re3 Rh8
$1 {It turns out that the advance g4-g5 is more dangerous for White.} 29. Kg1
Qd8 {[%csl Bh4,Bh8]} 30. e5 $2 {[%csl Bg1] After this mistake White`s position
quickly collapses.} ({Better would have been} 30. g5 hxg5 31. hxg5 Kg8 32. Bg2
{with a normal position.}) 30... Rd7 $1 {[%cal Bd6e5]} 31. g5 $2 (31. exd6 Rxd6
32. Rxd6 Qxd6 $17) 31... dxe5 32. Rxd7 Nxd7 $19 33. Qc2+ g6 34. Rd3 Qc7 35. h5
Nc5 36. hxg6+ fxg6 37. Bxe6 Nxe6 38. Rh3 Qc5+ 39. Kh2 Nxf4 40. Rxh6+ Kg8 {
0-1 White resigns.} 0-1

