[EventDate "2020.??.??"]
[WhiteTeam "Beer Sheva"]
[BlackTeam "Erevan MIKA"]

{The current World Champion Magnus Carlsen is famous for his sense of danger.
The position on the board arose in his game against the Israeli GM Alexander
Huzman. Black's position looks strategically promising. He has almost
unchallenged control on the light squares. In order to achieve the full
success he would only need to play ... Ne6, but then we notice the only
imperfection in his position the weakness of the c6-pawn. As mentioned in the
introduction, we should always look for dangerous tendencies. If White
exchanges the queens by means of Qc4, Black will have difficulties to
coordinate his pieces. Carlsen found a spectacular way to solve his
coordination problems.} 17... Kd7 $3 {[%cal Gd8e6,Gh8c8] The king bravely
steps closer to the centre, although most of the pieces are still on the board.
The main reason why this works is Black's stability on the light squares. Let
us check the alternatives in order to convince ourselves that this is the
strongest move, indeed.} (17... O-O 18. Qc4 $14 {and it is not likely that
Black is going to connect his rooks with ...Ne6 soon.}) (17... g5 $5 {Actually
this is the most viable alternative to the game move.} 18. h3 h5 19. Qc4 g4 20.
Qxd5 cxd5 21. hxg4 hxg4 22. Nh2 Rg8 23. Bf4 Ne6 24. Rd1 Rc8 25. Nf1 Rc4 26. Ne3
Rxd4 27. Nxd5 Rxd1 28. Rxd1 {, and White still retains some light initiative,
as the black rook needs to take care of the g4-pawn.}) (17... b5 18. Qb3 {
offers White a consistent initiative against Black's weakened queenside,
mainly due to his advance in development.} Ne6 19. Rab1 a6 20. a4 Qxb3 21. Rxb3
Kd7 22. axb5 axb5 23. d5 cxd5 24. Rxb5 $16 {Despite the queen exchange (or
maybe precisely because of it) the king feels much less secure on d7 than in
the game.}) (17... a5 {, planning . ..Rc8 and ..Ne6.} 18. Rcb1 $1 {Now that
there is a new target on a5, it is better to keep one rook on a1.} b5 (18...
Rb8 19. Qb3 Qxb3 20. Rxb3 {, threatening Bxa5, forces Black to continue to
weaken his queenside:} a4 21. Rd3 O-O 22. Rb1 Ne6 23. Rc3 Rfc8 24. Rbc1 $16 {
threatening both Rxc6 and d4-d5.}) 19. Qb3 Qxb3 20. axb3 $16 {and the a5-pawn
is in danger.}) 18. Bb4 (18. Rc3 Ne6 19. Rac1 Rhc8 {[%cal Bc8c7,Ba8c8,Bd7e8,
Be8f8,Bf8g8]} 20. Be3 Rc7 {, followed by ...Rac8 and, if needed, the king's
evacuation. Black would keep all the initial strategic trumps and solve his
problems of coordination.}) 18... b5 {Under the given circumstances Black is
prepared for the queenside expansion, as this will be done with a gain of time,
allowing him to complete his development in the process.} 19. Qa3 Bxb4 20. Qxb4
a5 21. Qb3 Ne6 22. Rxc6 $5 {White feels that he loses ground and decides to
play for an attack before Black completes his development. But his combination
can only lead to a draw at best.} (22. Rab1 {is not effective due to the simple
} Rab8 {and Black defends all the important squares.}) 22... Qxc6 (22... Qxb3
$2 23. Rd6+) (22... Kxc6 $2 23. Rc1+) 23. d5 Qc4 (23... Qb7 $5 24. dxe6+ fxe6
25. Rd1+ Ke7 26. Rd6 Rhd8 27. Qxe6+ Kf8 {makes White's compensation
questionable as the f3-knight is pinned.}) 24. dxe6+ Kxe6 {The start of an
incredibly safe king's march.} 25. Nd4+ Kd5 26. Qf3+ Kxd4 {Ole!!!} 27. Qe3+ $2
(27. Re1 $1 Kc5 28. Qe3+ Qd4 29. Rc1+ Kd5 30. Qb3+ Kxe5 31. Re1+ Kf6 32. Qf3+
Kg6 33. Re4 Qf6 34. Rg4+ Kh6 35. Rh4+ Qxh4 36. gxh4 f6 37. Qf4+ Kh5 38. Qf5+
Kh6 39. Qf4+ Kg6 40. Qg4+ Kf7 41. Qd7+ {with a perpetual.}) 27... Kd5 28. Rd1+
Ke6 29. Rd6+ Ke7 30. Qg5+ Ke8 $19 {The king has returned where his glorious
story started many moves earlier. White's attack does not compensate for the
missing rook.} 31. e6 Rc8 32. exf7+ Qxf7 33. Rd3 Qb7+ 34. Kh3 {No, it is not
the same thing. Not all the king's advances are glorious.} Rf8 35. Qh5+ Ke7 36.
Re3+ Kd8 37. Rd3+ Kc7 38. Rd5 Rce8 39. Rc5+ Kd6 {Once he has tasted the mirage
of high altitudes the king cannot resist returning to the center.} 40. Rxb5
Qc8+ 41. Kh4 {Jealousy?} Qc4+ 42. g4 Qd4 {0-1 White resigns.} 0-1

[Event "Candidates Tournament"]
[Site "Zuerich"]
[Date "1953.??.??"]
