[White "Reshevsky, Samuel Herman"]
[Black "Petrosian, Tigran V"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[ECO "E58"]
[Annotator "GM Grigor Grigorov"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "3rq1k1/4rppp/2n3b1/pp2P3/2pP1QB1/P1P1R3/1B4PP/4R1K1 b - - 0 25"]
[PlyCount "32"]
[EventDate "2020.??.??"]

{Another player with great feeling of danger was the former World Champion
Tigran Petrosian. He was often able to predict dangerous tendencies which
could develop in the long run. The next classical example is a must-know for
every player. White enjoys a strong pawn centre and a pair of bishops.
Moreover, he has a clear plan to develop his advantage. After Bf3 followed by
d4-d5, the central pawns would start rolling. Another dangerous idea is e5-e6.
Petrosian prevents these ideas with} 25... Re6 $1 {[%cal Gc6e7,Ge7d5] The
classical exchange sacrifice allows Black to take the control of the light
squares. Black is preparing the manoeuvre... Ne7-d5.} ({After} 25... Ra7 26. e6
f6 27. a4 Ne7 28. Bf3 b4 $140 (28... bxa4 29. Ba3) 29. d5 Nxd5 30. Bxd5 Rxd5
31. Qxc4 {Black's position is very dangerous.}) 26. a4 $5 (26. Bxe6 fxe6 $44 {
[%cal Bc6e7,Be7d5]}) 26... Ne7 $1 {Played in the right moment.} ({The
alternative} 26... b4 $2 {would have allowed} 27. d5 $1 Rxd5 28. Bxe6 fxe6 29.
Qxc4 $16 {with a big advantage for White.}) 27. Bxe6 fxe6 {[%cal Ge7d5] The
complete control of the light squares provides more than sufficient
compensation for the exchange.} 28. Qf1 (28. Qf2 $6 Nd5 29. Rf3 b4 $15) 28...
Nd5 29. Rf3 Bd3 30. Rxd3 $1 {Otherwise Black plays b5-b4.} cxd3 31. Qxd3 b4 $5
(31... bxa4 32. Ba3 (32. c4 Nb4) 32... Qg6 33. Qd2 Rb8 34. c4 Nb4 $13 {[%cal
Gb4c2] but the text is simpler.}) 32. cxb4 (32. c4 $6 Nb6) 32... axb4 {White`s
extra pawn does not play any role because of the blockade on d5-square.} ({
Another option would have been} 32... Nxb4 33. Qb3 (33. Qb5 Qxb5 34. axb5 Rb8)
33... Nd5 34. Ba3 Rb8 35. Qc4 Nb6 36. Qc7 Nd5 $1 (36... Nxa4 $2 37. Rf1 $18)
37. Qxa5 Ra8 38. Qd2 Rxa4 $11 {with equality.}) 33. a5 Ra8 34. Ra1 Qc6 35. Bc1
Qc7 36. a6 Qb6 37. Bd2 b3 38. Qc4 h6 (38... b2 39. Rb1 Qxa6 40. Qxa6 Rxa6 41.
Rxb2 Ra4 $11) 39. h3 b2 40. Rb1 Kh8 (40... Qxa6 41. Qxa6 Rxa6 42. Rxb2 Ra4 $11)
41. Be1 {1/2-1/2 The game is a draw.} 1/2-1/2

[Event "URS-ch43 Final"]
