[FEN "r1b2rk1/2q1bppp/p2p1n2/1ppPp3/2n1P1P1/2P2N1P/PPB2P2/R1BQRNK1 b - - 0 15"]
[PlyCount "13"]
[EventDate "2020.??.??"]

{Let's proceed with another instructive example which illustrates the
prophylactic thinking of Petrosian. It is already clear how White will develop
his kingside play - Ng3, Kh1, Rg1 and Nf5. On the other hand, Black's
queenside counterplay is rather slow. Therefore, Black must act now.} 15... h5
$1 {[%cal Bf1g3,Bg1h2,Be1g1,Bg3f5,Bg4g5] Just in time! Black should play this
move before White's Ng3.} ({Let's see how the game might develop if Black
plays passively. In one of the early games, he opted for} 15... Rd8 {when
White can easily prepare his kingside attack. The next moves are quite logical.
} 16. Ng3 g6 17. Kh2 Ne8 18. Rg1 Ng7 19. b3 Nb6 20. Bh6 Bf8 21. Qd2 {[%cal
Gg1g2,Ga1g1] White managed to mobilize all his pieces. He is now ready to
double the rooks on the g-file.} Qe7 22. Rg2 f6 {This move allows} 23. g5 Nd7
24. Rag1 fxg5 25. Bxg5 {White's attack is very strong. Later on, White has
converted his advantage.} Nf6 26. Nh4 Re8 27. Bd1 Ra7 28. f4 Qd8 29. f5 Be7 30.
Kh1 Rf8 31. fxg6 h6 32. Bxf6 Bxf6 33. Qxh6 Ne8 34. Ngf5 Bxf5 35. Nxf5 Qc7 36.
g7 Nxg7 37. Nxg7 Bxg7 38. Rxg7+ Qxg7 39. Rxg7+ Rxg7 40. Bg4 {1-0 (40) Colon
Romero,A-Benkner,O Moscow 1956}) 16. gxh5 {This move is not desirable, but the
alternatives are not better.} ({After} 16. g5 $2 Nh7 17. h4 g6 {[%cal Gf7f6,
Bc8g4] Black is better. He can use the kingside weaknesses by means of ...Bg4
and ...f7-f6.}) ({In a case of} 16. N3h2 {, Black would play} hxg4 17. hxg4 Nh7
{[%csl Gf4,Gg5][%cal Ge7g5] preparing ...Bg5. After exchanging the
dark-squared bishops, Black can make use of the weak dark squares.}) 16... Bxh3
17. N3h2 g6 $1 {[%cal Gg8g7,Gf8h8] It turns out that Black is the one who will
attack on the kingside. With his last move, he prepares ...Kg7 followed by ...
Rh8.} 18. Ng3 Kg7 19. Kh1 Rh8 20. Rg1 Kf8 21. a4 Nb6 $15 {Black was already
slightly better.} *

