{Here White is planning to open the h-file by Qg5 with h4-h5 to follow.
Therefore Black`s king must leave the dangerous zone.} 22... Kf8 $1 23. Qg5 Ke8
24. Rac1 Kd7 25. h5 gxh5 26. Rxh5 Rg8 27. Rh7 Kc8 {In result, already White
has problems because of the defects in his pawn structure and the passive
bishop.} 28. Qh4 Qg6 29. Rh8 Rxh8 30. Qxh8+ Kb7 31. Qf8 {This penetration can
be easily parried.} Rc8 32. Qd6 Qe8 $1 {Intending to drive away white queen
from d6.} 33. a4 Rd8 34. Qa3 Qe7 $1 35. Qc3 {The exchange of queens leads to a
difficult endgame for White in view of Black`s pawn majority on the queenside.}
Rc8 36. Bd2 g5 37. Qc2 $2 ({It seems that White`s best chance was} 37. a5 $5 b5
38. a6+ $1 Kxa6 39. Qb2 {, for example:} Kb6 40. Bb4 Qb7 41. Bc5+ Kc7 42. Bd6+
Kb6 43. Bc5+ {with repetition of moves.}) 37... f4 $1 {Threatening f4-f3.} 38.
gxf4 gxf4 39. Bxf4 Rg8+ 40. Bg3 $2 ({It was necessary to move the king away
from the g-file by} 40. Kf1 Nxd4 41. Qb2) 40... Nxd4 41. Qc3 Ne2 $1 42. Qc6+
Kb8 43. Re1 ({After} 43. Rh1 Qg7 $1 {is decisive.}) 43... Nf4+ 44. Kf1 Nxd3 45.
Rb1 Qf7 {[%cal Gg8g3]} 46. Qd6+ Kb7 47. Ke2 Rc8 $1 ({Also strong was} 47... Qh7
$1 48. Qxe6 $140 Nf4+ 49. Bxf4 Qc2+ $1 50. Ke3 (50. Bd2 Qc4+ $1 51. Kd1 Rg1+
52. Be1 Qd3+ 53. Kc1 Qc3+ 54. Kd1 Rxe1#) 50... Qe4+ 51. Kd2 Qxf4+ 52. Ke2 Qc4+
$1 53. Kd2 Qa2+ $1 {winning.}) 48. a5 Rc2+ $1 $19 49. Kf1 (49. Kxd3 Qf5+ $19) (
49. Ke3 Nc5 $1 50. axb6 Rc3+ 51. Kd4 Rc4+ 52. Ke3 d4+ 53. Ke2 Qh5+ $19) (49.
Kd1 Rc4 50. axb6 Nxf2+ $1 51. Ke2 (51. Bxf2 Qf3+ $19) (51. Ke1 Qh7 $19) 51...
Qh5+ 52. Ke3 Qh6+ 53. Kf3 (53. Kxf2 Rc2+ 54. Kf3 Qh5+ 55. Ke3 Re2+ 56. Kd4 Qg4+
$19) 53... Rc3+ 54. Ke2 (54. Kxf2 Qd2+ 55. Kf1 Rf3+ $19) 54... Rc2+ 55. Kf3
Qh5+ $19) 49... Nxf2 {[%cal Gf2e4]} 50. Rxb6+ axb6 51. Qxb6+ Kc8 52. Qa6+ Kb8
53. Qb6+ Qb7 54. Qd6+ Qc7 0-1

