{This position was reached in the game Shirov - Gavrikov, 1994. We can already
notice some tendencies which are dangerous for Black. White's concrete threat
is the advance c4-c5. Another long-term idea would be to remove the knight,
double the rooks on the b-file and invade Black's position via b7. After
taking into consideration all these ideas, Gavrikov took preventive measures.
Black has to reckon with the advance c4-c5 and the following preventive move
decreases the danger.} 26... Rc7 $1 27. Nd2 {[%cal Gb1b3,Gf1b1] Intending to
double the rooks on the b-file.} ({Now} 27. c5 $6 d5 28. Qxa6 {will not attack
the rook and Black can create counterplay by} dxe4 $1 (28... d4 $6 29. Bd2 Nxc5
30. Nxc5 Bxc5 31. a5 $16) 29. fxe4 Rxf1+ 30. Rxf1 Qxe4 $132) ({more dangerous
for Black looks} 27. Na5 {However, it seems that also here he has adequate
counterplay after} Nc5 28. Bxc5 Rxc5 29. Nb7 Rcc7 30. Nxd6 Bxd6 31. Qxd6 Rxc4 {
for example:} 32. Qxa6 (32. Qxe5 Rxa4 33. Rb6 Rf6) 32... Rc2 33. Rf2 Rxf2 34.
Kxf2 Qxe4 35. Rb8+ Kh7 36. Qxe6 Qd4+ 37. Ke2 Rd7 $5 (37... Rc7 38. Qg8+ Kg6 39.
Qb3) 38. Qf5+ g6 39. Qf6 ({In case of} 39. Qc2 {Black has} e4 $1 {which leads
to a perpetual -} 40. Qxe4 (40. fxe4 $4 Rf7 $19 {[%cal Gf7f2]}) 40... Qd2+ 41.
Kf1 Qc1+ 42. Kf2 ({or} 42. Qe1 Rd1 43. Rb7+ Kg8 44. Rb8+ Kf7 45. Rb7+ $11)
42... Rd2+ 43. Kg3 Qc7+ 44. Kh3 Qxb8 45. Qe7+ Kg8 46. Qe6+ Kg7 47. Qe7+ $11)
39... Qd1+ 40. Kf2 Rd2+ 41. Kg3 Rxg2+ $1 42. Kxg2 Qe2+ 43. Kg3 Qe1+ 44. Kh3
Qf1+ $11) 27... Be7 $1 {[%cal Gf7f8,Gf8c8] Vacating the f8-square for Rf7.} 28.
Rb3 Rf8 29. Rfb1 Rfc8 30. Rb7 Qe8 {Just in time.} 31. Rxc7 {with draw offer
which was accepted.} (31. Rxc7 Rxc7 32. c5 $140 $6 Nxc5 33. Bxc5 Rxc5 34. Qxa6
Rc2 $132) 1/2-1/2

