[EventDate "2020.??.??"]

{The position was reached in the game Carlsen - Anand. Black is in a difficult
situation due to his vulnerable king and inferior pawn structure. Our first
task is to see how White can develop his advantage. A closer look at the
position would allow us to see two possible ideas: 1) Nh3 followed by Qh6 and
Ng5 2) Re5 followed by Rfe1 In order to prevent these ideas from happening,
Black should have played the prophylactic} 24... Qd6 $1 {I find this best.
Black prevents ...Re5 (which now requires Nd3) and prepares an antidote to Nh3,
too.} 25. Nd3 {, although after} (25. Nh3 e5 {[%csl Be5]} 26. Qh6 Ne6 {[%csl
Bg5] and everything is fine for Black already.}) 25... a5 $14 {Black has
chances to keep the balance.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Elimination Method"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Grigor Grigorov"]
[PlyCount "0"]

{The second part of the lecture deals with the so-called "Elimination method".
Even though it can be used in different situations, this method is very
effective when our king is under attack. The logic is quite simple. We need to
find the only defence by rejecting all the bad moves. Even though this might
sound simple, the method is far from easy. The problem is that it is very
difficult to prove that other moves are bad. The process of elimination
requires the ability to constantly refute our own ideas. In order to be able
to refute our ideas, we need to find all the available resorces for the
opponent. That's how the prophylactic thinking interferes with the elimination
method. In order to make the elimination process easier, I would suggest
following the step-by-step guide: 1) Discover ALL the threats of your opponent.
At this stage, defining his candidate moves will make your job easier. 2) By
defining your candidate moves, try to find ALL possible defences. 3) Start
looking for a refutation of your ideas. You try to refute your candidate moves
one by one. 4) After refuting the wrong moves, you play the correct one. Quite
obviously, refuting our own ideas is the most difficult part of the job. Very
often, with a low level of prophylactic thinking and calculation just fail to
refute their own ideas. Besides prophylactic thinking and good calculation
skills, at this stage, we need mental toughness as well. When you see that all
the natural defences just don't work, it is very easy to get frustrated.
Therefore, when you are about to surrender, force yourself to keep looking for
possibilities.}  *

[Event "RUS-chT 19th"]
[Site "Sochi"]
[Date "2012.??.??"]
[Round "7"]
[White "Dobrov, V.."]
[Black "Timofeev, A.."]
[Result "1-0"]
[Annotator "GM Grigor Grigorov"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "3r1nk1/p3r2p/5BpQ/1pp5/4q3/5R2/6PP/5RK1 b - - 0 32"]
[PlyCount "14"]
[EventDate "2020.??.??"]

{The following examples illustrate how the elimination method works in
practice. Let's try to find the best defence in this position. First of all,
we need to find all the threats of the opponent. His candidate moves are: 32.
Bxe7 as well as every possible retreat of the bishop. The first thing that I
would try to understand is if Bxe7 followed by Rf7 is a real threat. It is
easy to see that this is not a threat because Black can sacrifice his queen
for the rooks. In the resulting endgame, White can never win. Even if we
remove the queenside pawns, there should be a fortress on the kingside. All
the bishop moves on the long diagonal can be answered with ...Ne6. If we keep
looking for the ideas of our opponent, we would probably notice the idea 32.
Bg5. Besides the standard threat of Rxf8, White creates an additional one -
Re3. In the game, Black didn't notice this subtle bishop move and went} 32...
b4 $2 {[%cal Bf6e5,Bf8e6] which loses on the spot.} ({The correct defence
would have been} 32... Nd7 $1 {when the following sequence is possible.} 33.
Bxe7 Qxe7 34. Rf7 Qxf7 35. Rxf7 Kxf7 36. Qxh7+ Kf6 37. Qh4+ g5 38. Qf2+ Ke6 39.
Qa2+ Ke7 40. Qe2+ Kf6 41. Qxb5 $14 {Despite the fact that White would keep
playing for a win, Black has fair chances for a draw.}) 33. Bg5 $1 $18 {
[%cal Gf3e3,Gf3f8] White is already winning. Black is helpless against the
double threat.} Qd4+ (33... Nd7 34. Re3 $18) 34. Kh1 Qg7 (34... Ree8 35. Rf7
Rc8 36. Be7 $18) 35. Qh4 $1 (35. Qxg7+ Rxg7 36. Bxd8 Ne6 37. Re3 $18) 35... Rd4
(35... Ree8 36. Qc4+ Ne6 37. Bxd8 $18) (35... Rdd7 36. Bh6 Qf7 37. Qc4 $18) 36.
Rxf8+ $1 Qxf8 37. Rxf8+ Kxf8 38. Bxe7+ Ke8 39. Qe1 {1-0 Black resigns.} 1-0

[Event "Bundesliga 9798"]
[Site "Germany"]
[Date "1997.??.??"]
[Round "2.1"]
[White "Ftacnik, L.."]
[Black "Cvitan, O.."]
[Result "0-1"]
[Annotator "GM Grigor Grigorov"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r5k1/ppp2rbn/1P1P2n1/P3p2p/2N1Pp1q/2N2Ppb/4B1PP/R2Q1RBK w - - 0 23"]
[PlyCount "10"]
[EventDate "2020.??.??"]

{In this example, we have a typical King's Indian middlegame. Even though
White has completely won the battle on the queenside, Black launched a very
dangerous kingside attack. In this game, Ftacnik failed to see Black's idea
and played} 23. bxc7 $4 ({Finding Black's idea was not too difficult. His only
obvious candidate move is 23...Bxg2+. Later on, everything is forced - ... Qh3,
...Ng5, ...Nh4, and ...g2 mate. Since we can easily refute 23.Re1 and 23. hxg3,
the only remaining option is} 23. gxh3 $1 Qxh3 24. Rf2 $1 {Once again, this is
the only move.} gxf2 25. Bxf2 {[%csl Bh1]} axb6 26. Nd5 $1 {Since Black's
kingside play is over, White proceeds with his expansion on the other wing.
After} cxd6 27. Nxd6 Rff8 28. Nxb6 Rad8 29. Bf1 Qe6 30. Bc4 $18 {, White is
already winning.}) (23. Re1 Bxg2+ 24. Kxg2 Qh3+ 25. Kxh3 Ng5+ 26. Kg2 Nh4+ 27.
Kf1 g2+ 28. Kf2 Nh3#) (23. hxg3 fxg3 $19 {[%cal Gg6f4]}) 23... Bxg2+ $1 24.
Kxg2 Qh3+ $3 25. Kxh3 Ng5+ 26. Kg2 Nh4+ 27. Kh1 g2# 0-1

[Event "Match Capablanca-Marshall +8-1=14"]
[Site "New York"]
[Date "1909.??.??"]
[Round "11"]
[White "Marshall, F.."]
[Black "Capablanca, J.."]
[Result "0-1"]
[Annotator "GM Grigor Grigorov"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "4rkn1/p1q4p/1p2Q1p1/4P1N1/b1p4P/2P1P3/6P1/4R1K1 b - - 0 36"]
[PlyCount "15"]
[EventDate "2020.??.??"]

{In the next example, we shall see how Capablanca used the elimination method
in his game against Marshall. This fragment shows why it is so important to
take into consideration all the ideas of your opponent. For example, in this
position, most of the people would immediately spot White's move obvious
threat - 37.Rf1 Kg7 38.Rf7. The problem is, however, that in response to 37...
Kg7, White has an additional option - 38.Qxe8 followed by Nxe6 on the next
move. If you don't see this second idea, chances are that you would seriously
consider playing 36...Kg7. In this case, however, you would run into 37.Qxe8.
Another thing that you need to spot is that closing the f-file with a piece
does not work due to g4. By using the elimination method, Capablanca found the
move} 36... Re7 {[%csl Be8,Bf7][%cal Be6e8]} ({As mentioned, closing the
f-file does not help. For instance:} 36... Nh6 37. Rf1+ Nf5 38. g4 $18) ({or} 
36... Bc2 37. Rf1+ Bf5 38. g4 $18 {[%cal Be8e6,Bg5e6,Be6c7]}) (36... Kg7 $2 37.
Qxe8 $18 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Gg5e6,Ge6g7,Ge6c7]}) 37. Rf1+ Kg7 38. h5 Be8 $19 {
Being a piece up, Black is already winning.} 39. h6+ Kh8 (39... Nxh6 $2 40.
Qf6+ $18) 40. Qd6 Qc5 (40... Qxd6 $2 41. exd6 Rxe3 (41... Rd7 42. Rf8 $18) 42.
Rf7 $18) 41. Qd4 (41. Qxc5 bxc5 42. Rf8 Rxe5 43. Nf3 Re7 (43... Rh5 $1) 44. Ng5
$10) 41... Rxe5 42. Qd7 (42. Rf7 Nxh6 $19) 42... Re7 43. Rf7 Bxd7 {0-1 White
resigns.} 0-1

[Event "Toronto"]
[Site "Toronto"]
[Date "1989.??.??"]
[Round "3"]
[White "Wolff, P.."]
[Black "Dlugy, M.."]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Grigor Grigorov"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "3r4/1pq2pkp/p7/2bn2N1/6Q1/8/PPP3PP/1K2R3 b - - 0 29"]
[PlyCount "7"]
[EventDate "2020.??.??"]

{Now, we shall proceed with a difficult example in which the solution requires
mental toughness as well. Black's king is under fierce attack in this position.
The good news is that White doesn't have many threats. Besides the main threat
30. Ne6+, depending on the position, he can consider moves like Qf5 and Qh5 as
well. By using the method of elimination, Black could have found the best move
which is} 29... Rg8 $3 ({Before finding ...Rg8, Black should refute the
remaining candidate moves. For example, after a move like} 29... Nf6 $4 {
, Black is getting mated -} 30. Ne6+ Kh8 31. Qg7#) ({Another obvious move that
can be easily refuted is} 29... f5 $2 30. Ne6+ Kh8 31. Qxf5 $18) ({The move
which was a played in the game is a serious candidate move.} 29... Kh8 $6 {
After the forced sequence} 30. Qh5 Nf6 31. Nxf7+ Kg8 32. Nxd8 Nxh5 33. Re8+ Bf8
34. Rxf8+ Kxf8 35. Ne6+ Ke7 36. Nxc7 $18 {White had a technically winning
position.}) 30. Ne6+ ({After} 30. Re8 $2 Rxe8 31. Ne6+ Kf6 {, Black is winning.
}) 30... Kh8 31. Qxg8+ Kxg8 32. Nxc7 Nxc7 {with an equal position. In any case,
finding ...Rg8 is a difficult task because of 2 reasons: 1) Black fails to
accurately calculate the sequence after 29...Kh8 2) Lack of mental toughness
which will force us to keep looking for something better than 29...Kh8.} *

