[Black "Andersson, U.."]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Grigor Grigorov"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "3rr2k/1p2bppp/p1b2n2/2qp1PB1/7Q/1BN4R/PPP3PP/5R1K b - - 0 20"]
[PlyCount "9"]
[EventDate "2020.??.??"]

{In this position, White's threat is pretty obvious - 21.Bxf6 followed by 22.
Qxh7. By using the elimination method, Andersson found the only defence -} 
20... Kg8 $1 {, evacuating the king.} ({The only alternative that Black needs
to refute is} 20... h6 $2 $18 {which would be answered with} 21. Bxh6 $18 {
[%cal Rh6g7]} Nh7 22. Bxg7+ (22. Bg5 $18) 22... Kxg7 23. Qh6+ Kg8 24. Qxh7+ Kf8
25. Qh8#) {After this dubious move, Black gets the initiative.} 21. Bxf6 $6 ({
White should have played} 21. Rg3 $1 {[%cal Rg5f6]} Kh8 $1 (21... Kf8 $2 22.
Bh6 $1 $18) 22. Rh3 $10) 21... Bxf6 22. Qxh7+ Kf8 $44 23. Qh8+ (23. Qh5 $5 Re5
$1 $44 (23... Qf2 $2 24. Qh8+ Ke7 25. Qxe8+ $18)) (23. Rf4 Re5) 23... Ke7 24.
Qh5 (24. Re1+ $2 Kd7 $19) 24... Rd7 $1 {[%cal Ge7d8,Gd5d4] Planning ...Kd8
followed by . ..d5-d4. Black is already better.} *

[Event "Interzonal-13c"]
[Site "Biel"]
[Date "1985.??.??"]
[Round "16"]
[White "Sokolov, I.."]
[Black "Short, N.."]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Grigor Grigorov"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "3q1rk1/1p1npp2/3p2pQ/p7/Pn2P2B/1P3R2/4r1PP/R6K b - - 0 20"]
[PlyCount "10"]
[EventDate "2020.??.??"]

{A fantastic application of the elimination method was seen in the game
Sokolov - Short. Black is about to get mated and should defend precisely. What
are the threats? There are three obvious candidate moves - 21.Rh3, 21.Bf6 and
21.Bxe7. The easiest part of the job is to notice that 21.Bf6 is not dangerous
in view of 21...Nxf6 22.Rh3 Nh5. Slightly more difficult is to understand that
21.Bxe7 is not a real threat since after 21...Qxe7 22.Rh3, Black has 22...f6.
After making these short calculations, Black should focus on the move 21.Rh3
which creates a variety of threats - besides all the bishop moves, White
threatens Qh8(h7) followed by Bf6+ and Rh8 (mate) as well. By using the method
of elimination, Short found the move} 20... Qe8 $1 {[%cal Gf7f6] Preparing the
advance ...f7-f6.} ({Quite an instructive is the following line:} 20... Qb6 21.
Rh3 Qd4 {Black's idea is that 22.Bf6 runs into 22...Qxa1+ followed by 23...Rd1.
The queen also controls the h8-square, thus preventing 22.Qh8 followed by Bf6.
Nevertheless, one of White's ideas remains available -} 22. Qh7+ $1 Kxh7 23.
Bf6+ {with a mate to follow. That's why you should try to figure out all the
threats of your opponent.}) 21. Bf6 ({As we already know, the idea} 21. Bxe7
Qxe7 22. Rh3 {does not work -} f6 23. Qh8+ Kf7 24. Rh7+ Ke8 25. Rxe7+ Kxe7 $19
{Black is winning.}) 21... Nxf6 22. Rh3 Nh5 23. Rxh5 gxh5 24. Qg5+ Kh7 25.
Qxh5+ {with a perpetual.} *

[Event "Barcza mem"]
[Site "Debrecen"]
