[White "Lukacs, Peter"]
[Black "Gavrikov, Viktor"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "D93"]
[WhiteElo "2490"]
[BlackElo "2545"]
[Annotator "GM Grigor Grigorov"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/pp2ppbp/5np1/q1n1N3/5B2/1BN1P3/PP3PPP/2RQ1RK1 w - - 0 13"]
[PlyCount "30"]
[EventDate "1988.06.22"]
[EventType "tourn"]
[EventRounds "11"]
[EventCountry "HUN"]
[EventCategory "10"]

{In the next two examples, we shall see how my former trainer GM Viktor
Gavrikov used the elimination method to face a dangerous opening preparation.
In this position, White went} 13. Bxf7+ $5 {which was a surprise for Viktor.} (
{He only analyzed} 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 Be6 $132 {with enough counterplay.})
13... Rxf7 {In his comments to the game, Viktor writes, "At this moment I
could not understand White`s intentions, but Black has no choice here and
therefore this move was made immediately."} 14. Nxf7 Kxf7 15. b4 $1 Qxb4 16.
Nd5 Nxd5 {Once again, Black uses the elimination.} ({Bad is} 16... Qa3 $2 17.
Nc7 Rb8 18. Nb5 $18) ({and} 16... Qa5 {was rejected in view of} 17. Nxf6 Bxf6
18. Qd5+ Be6 19. Qxc5 Qxc5 20. Rxc5 {- if necessary, Black can sacrifice an
exchange after the played move.}) 17. Qxd5+ {Now became clear that after} Ne6 {
White is going to double with tempo his rooks on the c-file and win Bc8.} ({
But before calculating the consequences of the knight`s retreat Gavrikov
started analyzing the alternative} 17... Be6 18. Qxc5 Qxc5 19. Rxc5 Bxa2 {
when Black is ready to advance his a-pawn. However, the reply} 20. Be5 {
secures better prospects for White. For example:} b6 21. Rc2 Bb3 22. Rc3 Bxe5
23. Rxb3 $14 a5 $140 $6 24. Rxb6 a4 25. f4 $1 Bg7 26. Rf2 a3 27. Ra2 Bb2 $16) {
Therefore, Black concentrated on his attempts to avoid the loss of exchange
and finally the saving idea was found.} 18. Rc4 Qb2 {The most logical, because
here the queen is protected by Bg7.} 19. Rfc1 $2 {Consistent and bad.} ({
Correct was} 19. Rc7 $1 {[%cal Gd5c4]} Kf8 20. Rxc8+ Rxc8 21. Qxe6 Rc1 22. g4
Rxf1+ 23. Kxf1 {with an equal ending.}) 19... Bd7 $3 {The bishop cannot be
taken and in result Black has a decisive advantage.} 20. h3 (20. Qxd7 $2 Rd8
21. Qa4 b5 $19) (20. R4c2 Qb5 (20... Bc6) 21. Rc5 $140 $2 Rc8 $1 $19) 20... Rd8
$5 ({Or} 20... Bc6 21. Rxc6 $140 $2 bxc6 22. Rxc6 Qb1+ $1 23. Kh2 Qf5 $19) 21.
Qf3 (21. Bc7 Bc6 $19) ({it is interesting that after 6 weeks the same position
occurred in another game of Gavrikov which continued} 21. Qa5 a6 22. Bc7 Rc8
23. R4c2 Qb5 24. Qxb5 Bxb5 25. Bb6 Rc6 26. Rxc6 Bxc6 27. f3 Nf8 $1 28. Kf2 Nd7
29. Ba7 Be5 $1 30. e4 Bd6 31. Ke3 e5 {In resulting ending, White is helpless
against Black`s pawn majority on the queenside.} 32. Kd2 Ke6 33. Be3 Be7 34.
Kc2 b6 35. Kb2 Kd6 36. Rd1+ Kc7 37. h4 a5 38. h5 g5 39. h6 Nf8 (39... b5) 40.
Bd2 Ne6 41. Bc3 Bd6 42. Ka1 Nd4 43. Kb1 Ne2 44. Bb2 b5 45. Rd2 Nf4 46. a3 Ne6
47. Bc3 b4 48. axb4 axb4 49. Rxd6 {Desperation in a lost position.} Kxd6 50.
Bxb4+ Kd7 51. Kc2 Nf4 52. g4 Ne2 53. Bc5 Bb5 54. Kd2 Nf4 55. Ke3 Be2 56. Bb4
Bd1 {0-1 Beliavsky,A (2655) -Gavrikov, V (2545)/Moscow 1988/URS-ch}) 21... Ke8
22. R4c2 Qb5 23. Bg3 Bc6 24. Qg4 Qf5 25. Qb4 Rd3 {[%cal Gf5d5]} 26. Rc4 Qd5 27.
e4 Qb5 {and White decided to resign because he has no chances to save the game.
} 0-1

