[EventCountry "SUI"]

{In this position, White played} 10. e5 $5 {A new idea back then - at the
price of a pawn, White tries to seize the initiative and exploit the uncastled
position of the black king.} ({In this situation} 10. Bxf6 {will be met by}
Qxf6 {because the f4-pawn is not protected}) ({but deserves attention} 10. Nxc6
Bxc6 11. Qe3 Be7 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. e5 Be7 14. exd6 Bxd6 15. Ne4 Bxe4 16. Qxe4
O-O 17. Bd3 g6 18. h4 Qf6 19. Rdf1 {[%cal Gg2g4] 1-0 Grabarczyk,B (2345)
-Panchenko,A (2460)/Katowice 1993/(35)}) 10... dxe5 11. fxe5 Nxe5 12. Qg3 Ng6
$1 {Black removes his knight from the vulnerable square and closes the g-file
for the white queen. Gavrikov only needed to calculate the possible sacrifice
on b5, but the concrete variations showed that White doesn't have enough
attacking resources.} ({Before this choice was made (it took Viktor about 40
minutes) he analysed also the following moves-candidates:} 12... Bd6 $2 {
- creates a critical point which can be exploited by} 13. Nf5 exf5 14. Rxd6 {
and Black is in trouble}) (12... b4 $2 {- here strong is} 13. Nd5 $1 exd5 14.
Qxe5+ Qe7 (14... Be7 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Qxd5) 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Qxd5 Bh6+ 17.
Kb1 O-O 18. Bd3 {with the same evaluation}) (12... Nc4 $2 {- here unpleasant is
} 13. Bxc4 bxc4 14. Rhe1 {[%cal Gd1d8,Ge1e8] and Black´s position looks bad
too}) (12... Qb8 {- the drawback of this move is that Nf6 is less protected
and White has} 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Ne4 Be7 15. Qg7 Ng6 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 17. Qxf6 {
when Black must accept a worse ending after} Qf4+ 18. Qxf4 Nxf4 19. g3 Ng6 20.
Bg2 {with an advantage for White}) ({therefore he tried to improve the
previous variation by} 12... Qc7 {keeping the possibility to castle after an
exchange on f6, but unfortunately the position of the black queen is
vulnerable and White can continue} 13. Nf3 ({now dubious is} 13. Bxf6 $6 gxf6
14. Ne4 Be7 15. Qg7 $140 $2 O-O-O 16. Nxf6 $2 Ng6 $1 {[%cal Gc7e5]} 17. Nxd7
Qxd7 18. Qh6 (18. Be2 Bg5+ 19. Kb1 Rdg8 $19) 18... e5 $19) 13... Nfg4 (13...
Bd6 14. Rxd6 Qxd6 15. Nxe5) 14. Bf4 f6 15. Qxg4 (15. h3 $6 g5) 15... Nxg4 16.
Bxc7 Nf2 17. Bd3 {with slightly better prospects}) (12... h6 {- in this case
is possible} 13. Bxf6 gxf6 ({loses a piece} 13... Qxf6 $2 14. Ne4) 14. Ne4 {
and White has sufficient compensation for the pawn} ({or} 14. Be2)) 13. Ndxb5
$2 ({Was necessary} 13. Bd3) ({or} 13. Qf3 {with some compensation.}) 13...
axb5 14. Bxb5 (14. Rxd7 Kxd7 15. Bxb5+ Kc8 $19) (14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Bxb5 Ne5 (
15... Ra7 16. Rxd7 Bh6+ $1 (16... Rxd7 {gives White a chance to force the
perpetual check by} 17. Bxd7+ Qxd7 18. Qb8+ Ke7 (18... Qd8 19. Qb5+ $11) 19.
Qb4+ Qd6 20. Qb7+ Qd7 21. Qb4+) 17. Rd2+ (17. Kb1 Rxd7 18. Rd1 Ne5 19. Ne4 Bf8)
17... Ke7 18. Rhd1 $15) 16. Rhe1 Ra7 $17) 14... Qb6 $1 {White underestimated
this reply, which allows to parry White`s threats.} 15. Qf3 (15. Bxf6 Bxb5 $19)
(15. Bxd7+ Nxd7 $19) 15... Ra7 ({Stronger was} 15... Rb8 $1 $19 {with the idea
to meet} 16. Bxf6 {with} Bxb5) 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. Rxd7 Rxd7 18. Rd1 (18. Bxd7+
Kxd7 19. Rd1+ Ke7 20. Ne4 Bh6+ 21. Kb1 Rb8 22. Qxf6+ Kf8 $17) 18... Ne5 19.
Qxf6 Qe3+ {Defending with a tempo the e5-knight.} 20. Kb1 Rg8 {This is the
position Gavrikov was going for in his calculations. He evaluated it as
winning for Black.} 21. Qf1 $1 Rg4 $6 {An inaccuracy in time-trouble.} (21...
Qb6 $17) 22. Bxd7+ $2 ({We both missed the continuation} 22. Re1 $1 Qd4 (22...
Qf4 $143 23. Qxf4 Rxf4 24. Rxe5 Kd8 25. a4 $13) 23. Qe2 $1 {[%cal Ge1d1]} Kd8
$1 24. Rd1 Qf4 $1 (24... Qb4 $143 25. Qxe5 Rxd1+ 26. Nxd1 Qd4 27. Qb8+ Ke7 28.
Be2 $13) 25. h3 (25. Bxd7 Nxd7 26. Qd3 Qc7 27. Qxh7 Bg7 28. Qh5 f5 $17) 25...
Rg6 26. Bxd7 Nxd7 27. a4 {when Black has difficulties to convert his material
advantage.}) 22... Nxd7 23. Nd5 Qe5 0-1

