504,503,576,583,575,581,581,581,566,566,587,587,587]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3.
Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Nb8 (9... Na5
10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Nd7 12. d5 Nb6 13. Nbd2 Bd7 14. Nf1 Nb7 15. Ng3 g6 16. Bh6
Re8 17. Qc1 Qc7 18. Nh2 {[#] In a similar type of position compared to
Spassky's game, GM Saric shows its modern treatment - dynamic defence :} Nd8 {
The most flexible move.} ({Passive defences are slightly inferior:} 18... f6
19. f4 exf4 20. Qxf4 Kh8 (20... Nd8 21. Nf5) 21. Ng4 Bxg4 22. Qxg4 $14 Nc4 23.
Rf1 Ne5 24. Qd1 Bf8 25. Be3 Bg7 26. Ne2 Nd8 27. Nf4) ({and} 18... Qd8 19. Rf1 (
19. f4 Bh4) 19... Bf8 20. h4 $36) 19. f4 Bh4 $1 20. f5 $1 {[#] A strong
attacking idea, but Black has a good defense.} f6 $1 (20... Bxg3 21. Ng4 $1 Bh4
22. Bg5 $18) 21. Ng4 Nf7 {[%csl Gf7,Rg3,Gh4,Rh6] Black defenders keep contact
with white pieces, making it more difficult to attack.} 22. Rf1 Qd8 {
Everything is defended and white pieces are forced to retreat.} 23. Be3 Nc4 {
[%csl Gc4]} (23... Bxg3 $6 24. fxg6 hxg6 25. Nxf6+ Kg7 26. Bg5 $36) 24. Bf2 Bg5
25. Ne3 Kh8 {[%cal Ge8g8] Suddenly, Black shows attacking ambitions on the
kingside.} 26. b3 Nxe3 27. Bxe3 Rg8 28. Bxg5 Nxg5 29. Qe3 Qe7 30. h4 $2 (30.
Kh2 Rg7) 30... Nf7 31. Qf3 Nh6 32. fxg6 Rxg6 $19 {Good active defense lead to
attack on the same flank!} 33. Nf5 Bxf5 34. exf5 Rg4 35. Be4 Qg7 36. a4 b4 37.
cxb4 cxb4 38. Rac1 Rxh4 39. Rc4 Ng4 40. g3 Qa7+ 41. Rf2 Rh2 {0-1 (41) Aravindh,
C (2485)-Saric,I (2680) Doha 2014}) 10. d4 Nbd7 11. Nbd2 Bb7 12. Bc2 Re8 13.
Nf1 Bf8 14. Ng3 g6 15. a4 c5 16. d5 c4 17. Bg5 h6 18. Be3 Nc5 19. Qd2 Kh7 20.
Nh2 Bg7 21. Rf1 h5 22. f3 {[#] Black needs to take measures against the f3-f4
break.} Qe7 $2 {[#] Static treatment of this position will land Black in
trouble.} ({Among several alternatives, the most active defence was} 22... Kg8
23. Bg5 bxa4 $1 (23... Qc7) (23... Qb6) 24. Bxa4 Rf8 25. Bc2 a5 $132) (22...
Qc7 23. Bg5 Nfd7 (23... Kg8 24. Bh6 Bh8) 24. f4 exf4 25. Rxf4 Ne5 (25... f6 26.
Nxh5 gxh5 27. e5+) 26. Raf1 Ncd7) (22... Nfd7 23. f4 exf4 24. Rxf4 Ne5 25. Raf1
) 23. Bg5 (23. f4 $2 exf4 24. Rxf4 Nxd5 $1) 23... Qf8 24. f4 exf4 25. Rxf4 Nfd7
26. Raf1 Ne5 {[#] Black position seems solid at the moment, but Spassky breaks
through with a strong sacrifice:} 27. Nxh5 $1 gxh5 28. Qe2 Qh8 29. Rh4 Kg6 30.
Bd1 f5 31. Rxf5 Rf8 32. Qxh5+ Qxh5 33. Bxh5+ Kh7 34. Bf7+ Bh6 35. Rxh6+ Kg7 36.
Bf6+ Kxf7 37. Bxe5+ Ke8 38. Rxf8+ Kxf8 39. Bxd6+ Kg7 40. Ng4 1-0

