{[#]} 19... Bb5 $1 {After a long think, Black produced an apparently illogical
move, but in fact the strongest and most active defence.} ({In case of the
straightforward} 19... Rac8 {White could easily get into a passive and
slightly worse endgame after} 20. Rc1 Bb5 21. Bd1 $1 Rfd8 22. Rc5 $1 a4 (22...
Rd5 23. Bb3 Rxc5 24. dxc5) (22... e5 23. a4 Ba6 24. Rxa5) 23. f4 Rd6 24. Kf2
Rcd8 25. Ke3 $14) 20. a4 ({The key difference compared to a similar position
from the variation above} 20. Rc1 Rfd8 21. Rc5 {is that here Black can
activate his rook on the b-file:} Rab8 $1 22. Bd1 (22. Bxc6 Bxc6 23. Rxc6 Rb4
24. Kf1 Rbxd4 25. Rxd4 Rxd4 {with a likely drawn outcome.}) 22... Rd5 23. Bb3
Rd6 $1 24. a4 Ba6 25. Bc2 e5 26. Rxa5 Bc8 $132 {and Black gets sufficient
counterplay for the pawn thanks to active rooks.}) 20... Bc4 21. Bxc6 Rab8 $44
{Black has full compensation for the sacrificed pawn as there are several
targets to attack: d4, b2, and a4 after White has weakened his position with
20.a4. The remainder of the game confirms this assessment.} 22. d5 (22. Rc1 Rb4
) 22... Rfd8 23. Rad1 Rb6 24. dxe6 Rxd2 25. Rxd2 fxe6 26. Bf3 Bb3 27. Rd8+ Kg7
28. Rd7+ Kh6 29. Rb7 Rxb7 30. Bxb7 Bxa4 31. f4 e5 32. fxe5 fxe5 33. Kf2 Kg5 34.
Ke3 Kf6 35. Bd5 1/2-1/2

