{[#] In the preparation for the game and during the game itself, I have
noticed that my opponent was a one-sided player in a sense that he played
strictly tactically. He was very creative in finding ways to enliven his
pieces and start tactical sequences; however, he sometimes did this at the
expense of broader, strategic goals. With this in mind, I set up a small
psychological trap for him with my previous move 26.Rd1.} 26... d5 $2 {Based
on the profile explained above, I had a strong feeling that he would go for
this 'false activity'. He has been in a passive position for most of the game
and now he finally gets a chance to make a statement in the centre and
activate his passive bishop and rook. This implies a pawn sacrifice, which he
had surely prepared and assessed as 'giving compensation' because his pieces
suddenly become very active. There are two problems with this move, though.
Firstly, it lacks strategic focus - it is purely a tactical device. Now, if it
would work tactically, who cares about strategy. But what if it does not work
tactically? Then Black's position falls apart. And here we come to the second
problem with false activity - in such cases the validity of the sacrifice is
determined very superficially - mostly by scanning active potential of the
pieces and calculating a few variations that confirm it. It is a bit of
wishful thinking because one does not analyze what could go wrong with it as
deeply as one should. As I have seen this pattern many times in my practice, I
was able to anticipate it and find the antidote in advance.} ({It was
necessary to keep defending passively with} 26... Ne5 {and ...Ne5-f7, although
White would keep a clear positional advantage after something like} 27. Qb2 $16
{as Black has a shaky pawn structure and exposed king.}) 27. Qb3 Ne5 {Played
quickly, which confirmed my prediction that Black had planned the pawn
sacrifice.} (27... dxc4 {would keep the material balance, but Black's pawn
structure after} 28. Nxc4 {would be awful and this is pretty much winning
after:} Nb4 29. Rxd8+ Qxd8 30. a3 Nd5 31. Qb8 $18) 28. cxd5 exd5 29. Bxd5+ Kf8
{[#] This is the position that Black was going for, but so did I! His pieces
are seemingly active and he threatens to win back the pawn on h3. I believe
that his assessment was based on White defending the pawn on the next move
when he indeed gets some counterplay. However, I realized in advance that I do
not have to waste time protecting that pawn and that I would have a big
advantage by playing for positional domination with} 30. e4 $1 {It was
important not to be materialistic. This move solidifies the powerful bishop on
d5 and White can proceed increasing the pressure from there.} ({White has many
ways to defend the h3-pawn, but all of them have some positional or tactical
drawback, besides wasting time, of course:} 30. Kh2 Qd7) (30. Bg2 c4) (30. g4
h5) (30. h4 Bg4) 30... Bxh3 31. Qc3 {[#] As a result of playing for false
activity, Black ended up in an even worse position than the one he started
from. The potential energy of white pieces is about to transform into
something much more concrete; f2-f4 is a strong threat and after that, all the
other pieces will move in.} Bg4 32. Rc1 {reminding Black that he has some pawn
weaknesses as 'side-effects' of his false activity.} Rc8 33. f3 Bh3 34. Nc4 {
Due to the mating threat on h8, Black can not trade the knight, so he has to
retreat:} Nf7 35. Rb1 $1 {[#] and the last White piece joins the attack. Black
can not defend all his weaknesses any further.} Qg5 {one last attempt to be
active...} 36. f4 Qh5 37. Bxf7 Kxf7 38. Rb7+ Ke6 39. f5+ {This covers the
fifth rank, so Black can not defend against the Qc3-e5# and he resigned.} 1-0

