{[#] Ground rules for passive defence: 1. Make conversion difficult for your
opponent - difficult strategic decisions, tricky or long variations to
calculate 2. Wear him down or make him nervous with your resilient defence 3.
Do not lose faith and keep creating chances for yourself} 35... Rd8 36. Qc7 Rc8
37. Qe5 Qc5 {Keeping contact with d4-knight.} 38. Rb1 ({White could win with} 
38. Rh1 f6 39. Qe6+ (39. Qf4 Re8) 39... Bf7 {but probably did not find} 40. Qf5
$1 $18) 38... f6 {regrouping: Bg6-f7, take control of the e-file.} 39. Qf4 Qe7
{keeping contact with e2-pawn, while keeping Qe5 as an option.} 40. Rb6 ({
White spent some time evaluating the endgame after} 40. Rb8 Rxb8 41. Qxb8+ Kh7
{but decided against it. White is surely winning here, as well, but this is a
tricky strategic decision to make as he is also winning with the game
continuation.}) 40... Bf7 41. Kf3 {Before going Nf5, White wants to
overprotect the e2-pawn. However, this is the first sign of playing without a
sense of danger.} ({He could win with} 41. Nf5 $1 {but he did not bother
calculating the forced tricky variation:} Qxe2 42. g5 $1 d4 43. gxf6 Bd5+ 44.
Kg3 Qxd3+ 45. Kh4 $1 $18) 41... Qa7 $5 {A glimmer of hope - Qa1-h1 is the idea.
} 42. Qd6 $4 {White does not realize what Black's intentions are. He would
still be winning if he retreated the rook, but he probably lost patience faced
with Black's stubborn passive defence in a lost position.} (42. Rb4 $18) (42.
Rb1 $18) 42... Qa1 $1 {now the perpetual cannot be avoided.} 43. Rb8 Qh1+ 44.
Ke3 Qc1+ 45. Kf3 Qh1+ 46. Ke3 Qc1+ 1/2-1/2

