{[#]} 28... Nb7 {The idea was to use the position of the white king in order
to manoeuvre the knight to the square on which it should have landed a long
time ago - d7.} ({The alternative was} 28... f6 29. Nc4 Nc8 ({The rook endgame
after} 29... Nxc4 30. Rxc4 Rd6+ 31. Kc3 $16 {looks very difficult for Black.})
30. f4 Kd7 {but White can improve his position effortlessly with} 31. Nd2 $1 {
since every piece exchange makes his position better, as we can see in the
following lines:} Ne7 (31... Rd6+ 32. Rd4) (31... Nd6 32. Ne4) 32. Ne4 Nd5 33.
Rc4 Rxc4 34. Kxc4 $16) 29. Nc4 Nc5+ 30. Kd4 Nd7 31. Rb5 Kd8 {I decided to
entrench and wait for my fate - what else to do?} ({An attempt to start some
active play on the kingside, such as} 31... f6 {could always be neutralized -
White pieces are just placed much better. For example:} 32. f4 h6 33. b4 g5 34.
f5 $1 exf5 35. Rxf5 Ke6 36. Rd5 {[%csl Gd5,Rf6,Rh6] and black position is
critical.} f5 37. b5 $18) 32. b4 {My opponent continues with the
straightforward and logical play, preparing to get his outside passed pawn.} ({
However, from a technical point of view, there was no need to rush things 
(Black has no counterplay anyway) and preparing the creation of the second
weakness on the kingside with} 32. g4 $5 Kc7 33. h4 {might have been even more
methodical.}) 32... Kc7 33. f4 h5 34. a5 {The time for queenside breakthrough
has arrived.} ({Nevertheless, the 'two weaknesses' approach still had its
merits:} 34. h3 $5 Kc8 35. g4 hxg4 36. hxg4 Kc7 37. g5 Kc8 38. a5 bxa5 39. Rxa5
Kb8 40. Ra3 Nb6 41. Ne5 $16 {and compared to the game, White has one more
weakness to work with - the f7-pawn.}) 34... bxa5 35. bxa5 $2 {A serious
technical mistake. Even though it might seem more dangerous to create an
outside passed pawn on the more 'outside' file, the a-file would have been
more suitable for the rook.} ({White would obtain serious winning chances if
he had recaptured the other way} 35. Rxa5 {A possible line is:} f6 (35... Kb8 {
prevents rook's intrusion, but Black has literally nothing useful to play
after something like} 36. Ra2 $16) 36. Ra7+ Kd8 37. Ra8+ Rc8 38. Ra6 Rb8 39.
Kc3 Ke7 40. Ra7 $16 {Black's defence would hang by a thread.}) 35... f6 36. h3
{Logically, White proceeds to create the second weakness on the kingside with
g4-g5, etc. Once again, the position begins looking critical for Black since
there are no active options insight. However, here I found a strong piece
regrouping that my opponent had probably missed.} Ra6 $1 {[#] The idea behind
this move is twofold: 1. the king will take rook's place on c6, thereby
expelling the rook from the important fifth rank. 2. the rook will be
activated via the 8th rank. I already felt better about my chances when I
spotted this defensive scheme and the game continuation confirmed this
assessment:} 37. g4 hxg4 38. hxg4 Kc6 39. Rb1 Ra8 40. g5 Rd8 $5 {In the game,
I thought that this is an essential inclusion,} ({because in case of} 40...
fxg5 41. fxg5 Rd8 {White would have} 42. Ne5+ Nxe5+ 43. Kxe5 Rd5+ 44. Kf6 {
which looked scary, so I stopped calculating. However, further analysis
revealed that Black easily draws the rook endgame after} Rxa5 45. Kxg6 Kd5 46.
Kf6 e5 47. g6 e4 {etc.}) 41. Kc3 {There were a couple concrete variations that
I had to calculate to make 40...Rd8 work tactically. This was the main line,} (
{but there was also} 41. gxf6 Nxf6+ 42. Ke5 Nd7+ 43. Kxe6 Re8+ 44. Kf7 Rf8+ 45.
Kxg6 Rxf4 $11) ({and} 41. Ke3 $5 fxg5 42. fxg5 Rh8 $11 {and Black is fine in
either case.}) 41... fxg5 42. fxg5 Nc5 $1 {[#] This is the most direct way to
play for a draw. It was important to realize that White can be allowed to give
checks on b6 and e5 without fatal consequences.} 43. Ne5+ ({In case of} 43.
Rb6+ Kc7 44. Kb4 {Black obtains enough counterplay with} Nd3+ 45. Ka4 Rd4 $132)
(43. a6 Ra8 44. Ne5+ Kd5 45. Nxg6 Rxa6 $11) 43... Kc7 44. Kc4 (44. Nxg6 Ne4+
45. Kc2 Rd2+ 46. Kb3 Rd5 $11) 44... Rd5 45. Rb5 (45. Nxg6 Rxg5 $11) (45. Re1
Nb7 46. a6 Nd6+ 47. Kc3 Kb6 $11) 45... Ne4 $1 $11 {The final precision. White
cannot avoid simplifications and draw was soon agreed.} 46. Rxd5 exd5+ 47. Kxd5
Nxg5 48. Nxg6 Kb7 1/2-1/2

