{[#] White has a slight initiative in this symmetrical endgame. His rook is
dominant on d5-square, from where it puts pressure on the b5-pawn. Black's
dilemma, typical for many endgames, is: defend actively or passively?
Grandmaster Demchenko chooses the latter:} 44... Rc3 $5 {Most modern
grandmasters prefer to defend actively without a pawn than passively with
equal material. It is just more natural and easier to play that way. Of course,
whenever material is sacrificed, some long-term risk is involved, but who says
that the risk of going wrong while defending passively is not greater?} ({
That being said, there was nothing wrong with the passive defence, either:} 
44... Rb7 {Here, the only constructive plan I see for White is} 45. Nf2 {
targeting the b5-pawn via d1-c3.} (45. Nc5 {brings no improvement:} Ra7 46. Nb3
Rb7 $11 {and Black will slowly activate his kingside pieces.}) {However, Black
also has his racing horse:} 45... Nh8 $1 {First, it takes one step back, but
then...} 46. Nd1 Ng6 47. Nc3 (47. g3 h4 $11) 47... Nf4 48. Rxb5 Rxb5 49. Nxb5
Nd3 $11 {...it gets to the finish line just in time.}) 45. Nf2 Rb3 46. Rxb5 {
[#] Demchenko followed Tarrasch's rule and now his rook is in an excellent
position. It not only defends against the passed pawn but may also be used
actively along the b-file to target White's kingside. Here, Demchenko rushed
to activate his knight, as well:} Nd6 $5 {This implies that Black is ready to
give up his f6-pawn.} ({It was also possible to protect that pawn first:} 46...
Kf8 47. Rb8+ Ke7 48. Nd1 {and only then play} Nd6 {Now after} 49. Ke2 {Black
is just in time to deny the e3-square to white knight:} Nc4 $44 {Black's
activity is fully sufficient to hold the balance. For example:} 50. h4 gxh4 51.
Rb7+ Ke6 52. Rh7 h3 53. gxh3 Rxb4 54. Rxh5 Rb3 55. Rh8 Nd6 56. h4 f5 $11) 47.
Rb6 {Wojtaszek's logical move instigates a forced sequence:} Nc4 48. Rxf6 Kg7
49. Rc6 Ne3+ 50. Ke2 (50. Kg1 Rb1+ 51. Kh2 Nf1+ 52. Kg1 Ne3+ $11) 50... Nxg2
51. Nd3 Nf4+ 52. Nxf4 {[#] Everything was forced up to this point. Black has
an important decision to make: capture with the e-pawn to have an option of
g5-g4 breakthrough, or keep the structure blocked with ...gxf4? Demchenko's
choice} exf4 $6 {is not wrong, but it is practically more complicated} ({than} 
52... gxf4 {White has two options now, but none of them is sufficient to win:
1)} 53. Rc5 ({2)} 53. Rb6 h4 54. b5 Re3+ 55. Kf2 Rb3 $11) 53... Rxb4 54. Rxe5
Rb2+ 55. Ke1 Rb3 {Black draws thanks to his active rook.} 56. Rxh5 Rxf3 $11)
53. Rc5 Kg6 ({Black can not afford to take the b-pawn} 53... Rxb4 $2 {, like
in 52...gxf4 variation. After} 54. Rxg5+ Kh6 55. Rf5 Rb2+ 56. Ke1 {The f4-pawn
is hanging, so there is no time to play ...Rb2-b3.} Rb1+ 57. Kd2 Rb2+ 58. Kc3
Rh2 59. Rxf4 Rxh3 60. Kd4 $18) 54. b5 Rb2+ $4 {I imagine that Demchenko was
already in time trouble at this stage of the game and just had to play
something because this move loses quite trivially.} ({Instead, Black should
have proceeded with his breakthrough plan} 54... g4 {and after a few pawn
trades:} 55. hxg4 hxg4 56. fxg4 Re3+ 57. Kd2 (57. Kf2 Rxe4 58. Kf3 Rb4 $11)
57... Rxe4 {[#] we would reach 2 vs 1 rook endgame where the extra pawn is not
of much importance. The g-pawn is safely blocked by black king, so this
position is drawn. A likely variation would be:} 58. Rf5 Rb4 59. Kc3 Rb1 60.
Kc4 Rc1+ 61. Kd5 Rb1 62. Kc6 Rc1+ $1 {(a necessary intermediate check to force
White king in front of his pawn)} 63. Kb7 Rf1 64. b6 f3 65. Kb8 f2 66. b7 Kg7
67. Kc7 Rc1+ 68. Kd6 Rb1 $11) ({Another, albeit more complex, way to reach a
draw is:} 54... h4 $5 55. Rc6+ Kg7 56. b6 g4 $1 $11 {[#] and, again, the g5-g4
breakthrough saves the day. I suggest the reader figure out how exactly on his
own.}) 55. Kd3 Rb3+ 56. Kc4 Rxf3 57. b6 Rf1 58. Rb5 $18 {[#] It is white rook
that is behind the passed b-pawn now, which is bad news for Black. His
connected pawns on the kingside are no match for it.} Rc1+ 59. Kd5 Rd1+ 60. Kc6
Rd8 61. b7 g4 62. hxg4 hxg4 63. Rf5 g3 64. Rxf4 Kg5 65. Rf1 1-0

